# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ast-transformation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] An **abstract syntax tree** (**AST**) is a data structure used in computer science to represent the structure of a program or code snippet.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] It is a tree representation of the abstract syntactic structure of text (often source code) written in a formal language.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Each node of the tree denotes a construct occurring in the text.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] It is sometimes called just a **syntax tree**.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] The syntax is "abstract" in the sense that it does not represent every detail appearing in the real syntax, but rather just the structural or content-related details.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] For instance, grouping parentheses are implicit in the tree structure, so these do not have to be represented as separate nodes.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Likewise, a syntactic construct like an if-condition-then statement may be denoted by means of a single node with three branches.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] This distinguishes abstract syntax trees from concrete syntax trees, traditionally designated parse trees.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Parse trees are typically built by a parser during the source code translation and compiling process.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Once built, additional information is added to the AST by means of subsequent processing, e.g., contextual analysis.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Abstract syntax trees are also used in program analysis and program transformation systems.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Abstract syntax trees are data structures widely used in compilers to represent the structure of program code.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] An AST is usually the result of the syntax analysis phase of a compiler.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] It often serves as an intermediate representation of the program through several stages that the compiler requires, and has a strong effect on the final output of the compiler.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Languages are often ambiguous by nature.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] In order to avoid this ambiguity, programming languages are often specified as a context-free grammar (CFG).
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] However, there are often aspects of programming languages that a CFG can't express, but are part of the language and are documented in its specification.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] These are details that require a context to determine their validity and behavior.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] For example, if a language allows new types to be declared, a CFG cannot predict the names of such types nor the way in which they should be used.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Even if a language has a predefined set of types, enforcing proper usage usually requires some context.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Another example is duck typing, where the type of an element can change depending on context.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Operator overloading is yet another case where correct usage and final function are context-dependent.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] The design of an AST is often closely linked with the design of a compiler and its expected features.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] These requirements can be used to design the data structure for the AST.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Some operations will always require two elements, such as the two terms for addition.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] However, some language constructs require an arbitrarily large number of children, such as argument lists passed to programs from the command shell.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] As a result, an AST used to represent code written in such a language has to also be flexible enough to allow for the quick addition of an unknown quantity of children.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] To support compiler verification it should be possible to unparse an AST into source code form.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] The source code produced should be sufficiently similar to the original in appearance and identical in execution, upon recompilation.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] The AST is used intensively during semantic analysis, where the compiler checks for correct usage of the elements of the program and the language.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] The compiler also generates symbol tables based on the AST during semantic analysis.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] A complete traversal of the tree allows verification of the correctness of the program.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] After verifying correctness, the AST serves as the base for code generation.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] The AST is often used to generate an intermediate representation (IR), sometimes called an intermediate language, for the code generation.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] AST differencing, or for short tree differencing, consists of computing the list of differences between two ASTs.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] This list of differences is typically called an edit script.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] The edit script directly refers to the AST of the code.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] For instance, an edit action may result in the addition of a new AST node representing a function.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] An AST is a powerful abstraction to perform code clone detection.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Let ${\mathcal {O}}=\{{\mathcal {O_{\alpha }}}\}_{\alpha \in \mathrm {Arity} (S)}$ be an $\mathrm {Arity} (S)$ -indexed family of disjoint sets of *operators*.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] If o is an operator arity $(s_{1},\dots ,s_{n})s$ we say that o has sort s and has n arguments of sorts $s_{1},\dots ,s_{n}$ .
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Fix S be a finite set of sorts, and ${\mathcal {O}}$ an $\mathrm {Arity} (S)$ -indexed family of disjoint sets of *operators*.
[src:ast-transformation/abstract-syntax-tree] Let ${\mathcal {X}}=\{{\mathcal {X}}_{s}\}_{s\in S}$ be an S -indexed family of disjoint sets of variables.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A **parse tree** or **parsing tree** (also known as a **derivation tree** or **concrete syntax tree**) is an ordered, rooted tree that represents the syntactic structure of a string according to some context-free grammar.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] The term *parse tree* itself is used primarily in computational linguistics; in theoretical syntax, the term *syntax tree* is more common.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Concrete syntax trees reflect the syntax of the input language, making them distinct from the abstract syntax trees used in computer programming.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Unlike Reed-Kellogg sentence diagrams used for teaching grammar, parse trees do not use distinct symbol shapes for different types of constituents.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Parse trees are usually constructed based on either the constituency relation of constituency grammars (phrase structure grammars) or the dependency relation of dependency grammars.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Parse trees may be generated for sentences in natural languages (see natural language processing), as well as during processing of computer languages, such as programming languages.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A related concept is that of **phrase marker** or **P-marker**, as used in transformational generative grammar.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A phrase marker is a linguistic expression marked as to its phrase structure.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] This may be presented in the form of a tree, or as a bracketed expression.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Phrase markers are generated by applying phrase structure rules, and themselves are subject to further transformational rules.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A set of possible parse trees for a syntactically ambiguous sentence is called a "parse forest".
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A form of parse tree was in use as early as 1879 in Gottlob Frege's *Begriffsschrift* book.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A parse tree is made up of nodes and branches.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] In the picture the parse tree is the entire structure, starting from S and ending in each of the leaf nodes (John, ball, the, hit).
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] In a parse tree, each node is either a *root* node, a *branch* node, or a *leaf* node.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] In the above example, S is a root node, NP and VP are branch nodes, while John, ball, the, and hit are all leaf nodes.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Nodes can also be referred to as parent nodes and child nodes.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A *parent* node is one which has at least one other node linked by a branch under it.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] In the example, S is a parent of both NP and VP.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A *child* node is one which has at least one node directly above it to which it is linked by a branch of the tree.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Again from our example, hit is a child node of V.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A **nonterminal function** is a function (node) which is either a root or a branch in that tree whereas a **terminal function** is a function (node) in a parse tree which is a leaf.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] For binary trees (where each parent node has two immediate child nodes), the number of possible parse trees for a sentence with *n* words is given by the Catalan number $C_{n}$ .
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] The constituency-based parse trees of constituency grammars (phrase structure grammars) distinguish between terminal and non-terminal nodes.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] The interior nodes are labeled by non-terminal categories of the grammar, while the leaf nodes are labeled by terminal categories.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] The parse tree is the entire structure, starting from S and ending in each of the leaf nodes (*John*, *hit*, *the*, *ball*).
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Each node in the tree is either a *root* node, a *branch* node, or a *leaf* node.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A root node is a node that does not have any branches on top of it.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Within a sentence, there is only ever one root node.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A branch node is a parent node that connects to two or more child nodes.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A leaf node, however, is a terminal node that does not dominate other nodes in the tree.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] S is the root node, NP and VP are branch nodes, and *John* (N), *hit* (V), *the* (D), and *ball* (N) are all leaf nodes.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] The leaves are the lexical tokens of the sentence.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A parent node is one that has at least one other node linked by a branch under it.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] In the example, S is a parent of both N and VP.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A child node is one that has at least one node directly above it to which it is linked by a branch of a tree.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] From the example, *hit* is a child node of V.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] The terms *mother* and *daughter* are also sometimes used for this relationship.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] The dependency-based parse trees of dependency grammars see all nodes as terminal, which means they do not acknowledge the distinction between terminal and non-terminal categories.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] They are simpler on average than constituency-based parse trees because they contain fewer nodes.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] This parse tree lacks the phrasal categories (S, VP, and NP) seen in the constituency-based counterpart above.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Like the constituency-based tree, constituent structure is acknowledged.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Any complete sub-tree of the tree is a constituent.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Thus this dependency-based parse tree acknowledges the subject noun *John* and the object noun phrase *the ball* as constituents just like the constituency-based parse tree does.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] The constituency vs. dependency distinction is far-reaching.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Whether the additional syntactic structure associated with constituency-based parse trees is necessary or beneficial is a matter of debate.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Phrase markers, or P-markers, were introduced in early transformational generative grammar, as developed by Noam Chomsky and others.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] A phrase marker representing the deep structure of a sentence is generated by applying phrase structure rules.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Then, this application may undergo further transformations.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] Phrase markers may be presented in the form of trees (as in the above section on constituency-based parse trees), but are often given instead in the form of "bracketed expressions", which occupy less space in the memory.
[src:ast-transformation/parse-tree] As with trees, the precise construction of such expressions and the amount of detail shown can depend on the theory being applied and on the points that the query author wishes to illustrate.
[src:ast-transformation/program-transformation] A **program transformation** is any operation that takes a computer program and generates another program.
[src:ast-transformation/program-transformation] In many cases the transformed program is required to be semantically equivalent to the original, relative to a particular formal semantics and in fewer cases the transformations result in programs that semantically differ from the original in predictable ways.
[src:ast-transformation/program-transformation] While the transformations can be performed manually, it is often more practical to use a program transformation system that applies specifications of the required transformations.
[src:ast-transformation/program-transformation] Program transformations may be specified as automated procedures that modify compiler data structures (e.g. abstract syntax trees) representing the program text, or may be specified more conveniently using patterns or templates representing parameterized source code fragments.
[src:ast-transformation/program-transformation] A practical requirement for source code transformation systems is that they be able to effectively process programs written in a programming language.
[src:ast-transformation/program-transformation] The problem of building and integrating adequate front ends for conventional languages (Java, C++, PHP etc.) may be of equal difficulty as building the program transformation system itself because of the complexity of such languages.
[src:ast-transformation/program-transformation] To be widely useful, a transformation system must be able to handle many target programming languages, and must provide some means of specifying such language-specific front-ends.
[src:ast-transformation/program-transformation] Spoon is an example of a Java-specific program transformation library that addresses this challenge by providing a full front-end for Java, exposing an AST-based API for implementing analyses and transformations of Java source code.
[src:ast-transformation/program-transformation] In other words, a refinement of a program is *more defined* and *more deterministic* than the original program.
[src:ast-transformation/program-transformation] If two programs are refinements of each other, then the programs are equivalent.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] In mathematics, linguistics, computer science, and logic, **rewriting** covers a wide range of methods of replacing subterms of a formula with other terms.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Such methods may be achieved by **rewriting systems** (also known as **rewrite systems**, **rewrite engines**, or **reduction systems**).
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] In their most basic form, they consist of a set of objects, plus relations on how to transform those objects.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] One rule to rewrite a term could be applied in many different ways to that term, or more than one rule could be applicable.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Rewriting systems then do not provide an algorithm for changing one term to another, but a set of possible rule applications.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] When combined with an appropriate algorithm, however, rewrite systems can be viewed as computer programs, and several theorem provers and declarative programming languages are based on term rewriting.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] In logic, the procedure for obtaining the conjunctive normal form (CNF) of a formula can be implemented as a rewriting system.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] For each rule, each variable denotes a subexpression, and the symbol ( $\to$ ) indicates that an expression matching the left hand side of it can be rewritten to one matching the right hand side of it.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] In such a system, each rule is a logical equivalence, so performing a rewrite on an expression by these rules does not change the truth value of it.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Other useful rewriting systems in logic may not preserve truth values, see e.g. equisatisfiability.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Term rewriting systems can be employed to compute arithmetic operations on natural numbers.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] To this end, each such number has to be encoded as a term.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The simplest encoding is the one used in the Peano axioms, based on the constant 0 (zero) and the successor function *S*.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] For example, the numbers 0, 1, 2, and 3 are represented by the terms 0, S(0), S(S(0)), and S(S(S(0))), respectively.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The following term rewriting system can then be used to compute sum and product of given natural numbers.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] where the notation above each arrow indicates the rule used for each rewrite.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] where the last step comprises the previous example computation.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] In linguistics, phrase structure rules, also called **rewrite rules**, are used in some systems of generative grammar, as a means of generating the grammatically correct sentences of a language.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Such a rule typically takes the form ${\rm {A\rightarrow X}}$ , where A is a syntactic category label, such as noun phrase or sentence, and X is a sequence of such labels or morphemes, expressing the fact that A can be replaced by X in generating the constituent structure of a sentence.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] For example, the rule ${\rm {S\rightarrow NP\ VP}}$ means that a sentence can consist of a noun phrase (NP) followed by a verb phrase (VP); further rules will specify what sub-constituents a noun phrase and a verb phrase can consist of, and so on.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] From the above examples, it is clear that we can think of rewriting systems in an abstract manner.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] We need to specify a set of objects and the rules that can be applied to transform them.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The most general (unidimensional) setting of this notion is called an *abstract reduction system* or *abstract rewriting system* (abbreviated *ARS*).
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] An ARS is simply a set *A* of objects, together with a binary relation → on *A* called the *reduction relation*, *rewrite relation* or just *reduction*.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The word problem for an ARS is determining, given *x* and *y*, whether $x{\overset {*}{\leftrightarrow }}y$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] An object *x* in *A* is called *reducible* if there exists some other *y* in *A* such that $x\rightarrow y$ ; otherwise it is called *irreducible* or a normal form.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] An object *y* is called a "normal form of *x*" if $x{\stackrel {*}{\rightarrow }}y$ , and *y* is irreducible.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] If the normal form of *x* is unique, then this is usually denoted with $x{\downarrow }$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] If every object has at least one normal form, the ARS is called *normalizing*. $x\downarrow y$ or *x* and *y* are said to be *joinable* if there exists some *z* with the property that $x{\overset {*}{\rightarrow }}z{\overset {*}{\leftarrow }}y$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] An ARS is said to possess the Church–Rosser property if $x{\overset {*}{\leftrightarrow }}y$ implies $x\downarrow y$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] An ARS is confluent if for all *w*, *x*, and *y* in *A*, $x{\overset {*}{\leftarrow }}w{\overset {*}{\rightarrow }}y$ implies $x\downarrow y$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] An ARS is *locally confluent* if and only if for all *w*, *x*, and *y* in *A*, $x\leftarrow w\rightarrow y$ implies $x{\mathbin {\downarrow }}y$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] An ARS is said to be *terminating* or *noetherian* if there is no infinite chain $x_{0}\rightarrow x_{1}\rightarrow x_{2}\rightarrow \cdots$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] A confluent and terminating ARS is called *convergent* or *canonical*.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Important theorems for abstract rewriting systems are that an ARS is confluent iff it has the Church–Rosser property, Newman's lemma (a terminating ARS is confluent if and only if it is locally confluent), and that the word problem for an ARS is undecidable in general.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] A *string rewriting system* (SRS), also known as *semi-Thue system*, exploits the free monoid structure of the strings (words) over an alphabet to extend a rewriting relation, R , to *all* strings in the alphabet that contain left- and respectively right-hand sides of some rules as substrings.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Formally a semi-Thue system is a tuple $(\Sigma ,R)$ where $\Sigma$ is a (usually finite) alphabet, and R is a binary relation between some (fixed) strings in the alphabet, called the set of *rewrite rules*.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The *one-step rewriting relation* ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ induced by R on $\Sigma ^{*}$ is defined as: if $s,t\in \Sigma ^{*}$ are any strings, then $s{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}t$ if there exist $x,y,u,v\in \Sigma ^{*}$ such that $s=xuy$ , $t=xvy$ , and $uRv$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Since ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ is a relation on $\Sigma ^{*}$ , the pair $(\Sigma ^{*},{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }})$ fits the definition of an abstract rewriting system.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Since the empty string is in $\Sigma ^{*}$ , R is a subset of ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] If the relation R is symmetric, then the system is called a *Thue system*.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] In a SRS, the reduction relation ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}$ is compatible with the monoid operation, meaning that $x{\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}y$ implies $uxv{\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}uyv$ for all strings $x,y,u,v\in \Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Similarly, the reflexive transitive symmetric closure of ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ , denoted ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ , is a congruence, meaning it is an equivalence relation (by definition) and it is also compatible with string concatenation.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The relation ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ is called the *Thue congruence* generated by R .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] In a Thue system, i.e. if R is symmetric, the rewrite relation ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}$ coincides with the Thue congruence ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The notion of a semi-Thue system essentially coincides with the presentation of a monoid.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Since ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ is a congruence, we can define the factor monoid ${\mathcal {M}}_{R}=\Sigma ^{*}/{\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ of the free monoid $\Sigma ^{*}$ by the Thue congruence.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] If a monoid ${\mathcal {M}}$ is isomorphic with ${\mathcal {M}}_{R}$ , then the semi-Thue system $(\Sigma ,R)$ is called a monoid presentation of ${\mathcal {M}}$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] We immediately get some very useful connections with other areas of algebra.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] For example, the alphabet $\{a,b\}$ with the rules $\{ab\rightarrow \varepsilon ,ba\rightarrow \varepsilon \}$ , where $\varepsilon$ is the empty string, is a presentation of the free group on one generator.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] If instead the rules are just $\{ab\rightarrow \varepsilon \}$ , then we obtain a presentation of the bicyclic monoid.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Thus semi-Thue systems constitute a natural framework for solving the word problem for monoids and groups.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] In fact, every monoid has a presentation of the form $(\Sigma ,R)$ , i.e. it may always be presented by a semi-Thue system, possibly over an infinite alphabet.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The word problem for a semi-Thue system is undecidable in general; this result is sometimes known as the *Post–Markov theorem*.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] A **term rewriting system** (**TRS**) is a rewriting system whose objects are *terms*, which are expressions with nested sub-expressions.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] For example, the system shown under *§ Logic* above is a term rewriting system.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The terms in this system are composed of binary operators $(\vee )$ and $(\wedge )$ and the unary operator $(\neg )$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Also present in the rules are variables, which represent any possible term (though a single variable always represents the same term throughout a single rule).
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] In contrast to string rewriting systems, whose objects are sequences of symbols, the objects of a term rewriting system form a term algebra.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] A term can be visualized as a tree of symbols, the set of admitted symbols being fixed by a given signature.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] As a formalism, term rewriting systems have the full power of Turing machines, that is, every computable function can be defined by a term rewriting system.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Some programming languages are based on term rewriting.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] One such example is Pure, a functional programming language for mathematical applications.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] A *rewrite rule* is a pair of terms, commonly written as $l\rightarrow r$ , to indicate that the left-hand side *l* can be replaced by the right-hand side *r*.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] A *term rewriting system* is a set *R* of such rules.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] A rule $l\rightarrow r$ can be *applied* to a term *s* if the left term l matches some subterm of *s*, that is, if there is some substitution $\sigma$ such that the subterm of s rooted at some position *p* is the result of applying the substitution $\sigma$ to the term l.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The subterm matching the left hand side of the rule is called a **redex** or **reducible expression**.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] The result term *t* of this rule application is then the result of replacing the subterm at position *p* in *s* by the term r with the substitution $\sigma$ applied, see picture 1.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] In this case, s is said to be *rewritten in one step*, or *rewritten directly*, to t by the system R , formally denoted as $s\rightarrow _{R}t$ , $s{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}t$ , or as $s{\overset {R}{\rightarrow }}t$ by some authors.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] A term rewriting given by a set R of rules can be viewed as an abstract rewriting system as defined above, with terms as its objects and ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ as its rewrite relation.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] For example, $x*(y*z)\rightarrow (x*y)*z$ is a rewrite rule, commonly used to establish a normal form with respect to the associativity of * .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] That rule can be applied at the numerator in the term ${\frac {a*((a+1)*(a+2))}{1*(2*3)}}$ with the matching substitution $\{x\mapsto a,\;y\mapsto a+1,\;z\mapsto a+2\}$ , see picture 2.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Applying that substitution to the rule's right-hand side yields the term $(a*(a+1))*(a+2)$ , and replacing the numerator by that term yields ${\frac {(a*(a+1))*(a+2)}{1*(2*3)}}$ , which is the result term of applying the rewrite rule.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Altogether, applying the rewrite rule has achieved what is called "applying the associativity law for * to ${\frac {a*((a+1)*(a+2))}{1*(2*3)}}$ " in elementary algebra.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Alternately, the rule could have been applied to the denominator of the original term, yielding ${\frac {a*((a+1)*(a+2))}{(1*2)*3}}$ .
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Termination issues of rewrite systems in general are handled in *Abstract rewriting system#Termination and convergence*.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] For term rewriting systems in particular, the following additional subtleties are to be considered.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Termination even of a system consisting of one rule with a linear left-hand side is undecidable.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Termination is also undecidable for systems using only unary function symbols; however, it is decidable for finite ground systems.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] All these properties are satisfied by Toyama's examples.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] See Rewrite order and Path ordering (term rewriting) for ordering relations used in termination proofs for term rewriting systems.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Higher-order rewriting systems are a generalization of first-order term rewriting systems to lambda terms, allowing higher order functions and bound variables.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Various results about first-order TRSs can be reformulated for HRSs as well.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Graph rewrite systems are another generalization of term rewrite systems, operating on graphs instead of (ground-) terms / their corresponding tree representation.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Trace theory provides a means for discussing multiprocessing in more formal terms, such as via the trace monoid and the history monoid.
[src:ast-transformation/rewriting] Rewriting can be performed in trace systems as well.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] A source-to-source translator converts between programming languages that operate at approximately the same level of abstraction, while a traditional compiler translates from a higher level language to a lower level language.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] For example, a source-to-source translator may perform a translation of a program from Python to JavaScript, while a traditional compiler translates from a language like C to assembly or Java to bytecode.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] An automatic parallelizing compiler will frequently take in a high level language program as an input and then transform the code and annotate it with parallel code annotations (e.g., OpenMP) or language constructs (e.g.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Another purpose of source-to-source-compiling is translating legacy code to use the next version of the underlying programming language or an application programming interface (API) that breaks backward compatibility.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Transcompilers may either keep translated code structure as close to the source code as possible to ease development and debugging of the original source code or may change the structure of the original code so much that the translated code does not look like the source code.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Examples include Closure Compiler, CoffeeScript, Dart, Haxe, Opal, TypeScript and Emscripten.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] So called *Assembly language translators* are a class of source-to-source translators converting code from one assembly language into another, including (but not limited to) across different processor families and system platforms.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Intel marketed their 16-bit processor 8086 to be source compatible to the 8080, an 8-bit processor.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] To support this, Intel had an ISIS-II-based translator from 8080 to 8086 source code named CONV86 (also referred to as CONV-86 and CONVERT 86) available to OEM customers since 1978, possibly the earliest program of this kind.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] It supported multiple levels of translation and ran at 2 MHz on an Intel Microprocessor Development System MDS-800 with 8-inch floppy drives.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] According to user reports, it did not work very reliably.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Seattle Computer Products (SCP) offered TRANS86.COM, written by Tim Paterson in 1980 while developing 86-DOS.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Also, performing only a mere transliteration, the brute-force single-pass translator did not carry out any register and jump optimizations.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] The SCP version 1 of TRANS86.COM ran on Z80-based systems.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Once 86-DOS was running, Paterson, in a self-hosting-inspired approach, utilized TRANS86 to convert itself into a program running under 86-DOS.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Numbered version 2, this was named TRANS.COM instead.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Later in 1982, the translator was apparently also available from Microsoft.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Also named TRANS86, Sorcim offered an 8080 to 8086 translator as well since December 1980.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Like SCP's program it was designed to port CP/M-80 application code (in ASM, MAC, RMAC or ACT80 assembly format) to MS-DOS (in a format compatible with ACT86).
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] In ACT80 format it also supported a few Z80 mnemonics.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] The translation occurred on an instruction-by-instruction basis with some optimization applied to conditional jumps.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] The program ran under CP/M-80, MP/M-80 and Cromemco DOS with a minimum of 24 KB of RAM, and had no restrictions on the source file size.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Much more sophisticated and the first to introduce optimizing compiler technologies into the source translation process was Digital Research's XLT86 1.0 in September 1981.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] The program was written by Gary Kildall and translated .ASM source code for the Intel 8080 processor (in a format compatible with ASM, MAC or RMAC assemblers) into .A86 source code for the 8086 (compatible with ASM86).
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] XLT86.COM itself was written in PL/I-80 for CP/M-80 platforms.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] The program occupied 30 KB of RAM for itself plus additional memory for the program graph.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] On a 64 KB memory system, the maximum source file size supported was about 6 KB, so that larger files had to be broken down accordingly before translation.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Alternatively, XLT86 was also available for DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Although XLT86's input and output worked on source-code level, the translator's in-memory representation of the program and the applied code optimizing technologies set the foundation to binary recompilation.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] 2500 AD Software offered an 8080 to 8086 source-code translator as part of their XASM suite for CP/M-80 machines with Z80 as well as for Zilog ZEUS and Olivetti PCOS systems.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Since 1979, Zilog offered a Z80 to Z8000 translator as part of their PDS 8000 development system.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Advanced Micro Computers (AMC) and 2500 AD Software offered Z80 to Z8000 translators as well.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] The latter was named TRANS and was available for Z80 CP/M, CP/M-86, MS-DOS and PCOS.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] The Z88DK development kit provides a Z80 to i486 source code translator targeting nasm named "to86.awk", written in 2008 by Stefano Bodrato.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] It is in turn based on an 8080 to Z80 converter written in 2003 by Douglas Beattie, Jr., named "toz80.awk".
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] In 2021, Brian Callahan wrote an 8080 CP/M 2.2 to MS-DOS source code translator targeting nasm named 8088ify.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] The first implementations of some programming languages started as transcompilers, and the default implementation for some of those languages are still transcompilers.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] In addition to the table below, a CoffeeScript maintainer provides a list of languages that compile to JavaScript.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] When developers want to switch to a different language while retaining most of an existing codebase, it might be better to use a transcompiler compared to rewriting the whole software by hand.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Depending on the quality of the transcompiler, the code may or may not need manual intervention in order to work properly.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] This is different from "transcompiled languages" where the specifications demand that the output source code always works without modification.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] All transcompilers used to port a codebase will expect manual adjustment of the output source code if there is a need to achieve maximum code quality in terms of readability and platform convention.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] A transcompiler pipeline is what results from *recursive transcompiling*.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] By stringing together multiple layers of tech, with a transcompile step between each layer, technology can be repeatedly transformed, effectively creating a distributed language independent specification.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] XSLT is a general-purpose transform tool that can be used between many different technologies, to create such a derivative code pipeline.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] By repeating this process, one can turn A → B → C → D → E → F and then back into A(v2).
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] Some information will be preserved through this pipeline, from A → A(v2), and that information (at an abstract level) demonstrates what each of the components A–F agree on.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] In each of the different versions that the transcompiler pipeline produces, that information is preserved.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] It might take on many different shapes and sizes, but by the time it comes back to A (v2), having been transcompiled six times in the pipeline above, the information returns to its original state.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] This information which survives the transform through each format, from A–F–A(v2), is (by definition) derivative content or derivative code.
[src:ast-transformation/source-to-source-compiler] There are also debugging utilities that map the transcompiled source code back to the original code; for example, JavaScript source maps allow mapping of the JavaScript code executed by a web browser back to the original source in a transcompiled-to-JavaScript language.
